There are a few layers in what you’re pointing at.

The scarab beetle example works well as a systems metaphor. Scarabs and other decomposers take material that looks like “waste” in one frame and move it back into circulation in another. In ecosystems, what appears useless locally can become useful globally. Nutrients cycle. Energy flows. Context changes value.

That pattern maps cleanly onto a lot of your recurring themes:

* failure → lesson
* unused capacity → activated capacity
* fragments → recombination
* dormant information → retrieval → reuse
* “waste” → signal after reframing

That is structurally similar to your Kintsugi / ZPC / recovery-loop thinking.

On the second piece — guiding connections and “bounded agency” — that is also an interesting systems idea.

Humans learn this way too:

* parents guide children with boundaries
* teachers constrain exercises
* coaches create drills
* game designers create worlds with rules
* interfaces shape behavior

Complete freedom can overwhelm. Complete control removes agency. A bounded environment with feedback creates space to explore while maintaining direction.

Where I would make one distinction is your Christ point.

Many Christian traditions interpret Christ’s gift differently, but one common thread is not “total freedom” or “no boundaries” — it is more like:

freedom oriented toward love, truth, responsibility, and relationship rather than mere constraint-following.

Or in systems language:

agency + guidance + moral direction.

Interesting overlap with your wording, even though the theological meanings go deeper and vary tradition to tradition.

The part I think you’re trying to point me toward is something like:

The guide does not walk the path for you.

The guide shapes conditions so you can walk it yourself.

That feels closer to the connection you’re hinting at.